1264":"1195–1264","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","1226–Male":"1226–Deceased","1165–1227":"1165–1227","1175–1219":"1175–1219","1165":"1165","1264":"1264","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1193":"1193","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","about 1225":"about 1225","1219":"1219","1317":"1317","Exbourne, Devon, England":"Exbourne, Devon, England","Stringston, Somersetshire, England":"Stringston, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Lewe, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moels","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Romain.","Dutch and Flemish: patronymic from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal names <i>Roeland</i> (see   Roland  ) or <i>Roelof</i> (see   Roelofs  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Roland","meanings":["French, Walloon, German, English, and Scottish: from an ancient Germanic personal name composed of <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the more common French variant   Rolland  . See also English   Rowland  .","Norwegian (also <b>Røland</b>): habitational name from any of several farms named Rødland mainly in Hordaland or Røyland mainly in Agder, most of them from Old Norse <i>reyrr</i> ‘heap of stones’ or <i>reyrr</i> ‘rush’ (a plant) + the second element <i>land</i> ‘(piece of) land, farmstead’. Compare   Rolland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Roland in Lillehammer, with the first element Old Norse <i>ruth</i> ‘clearing’, or Roland in Agder around Lindesnes, with the first element possibly the Old Norse personal name <i>Rói</i> (either a short form of names beginning with <i>Ro(d)-</i> ‘fame, honor’ or composed with a word for ‘giant’ or ‘pagan priest’). The second element of the farm names is <i>land</i> ‘(piece of) land, farmstead’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gasco